{"id":"2112.14389","submitter":"Ali Hajbabaie","authors":"Mehrzad Mehrabipour and Ali Hajbabaie","title":"A Distributed Gradient Approach for System Optimal Dynamic Traffic\n  Assignment","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This study presents a distributed gradient-based approach to solve system\noptimal dynamic traffic assignment (SODTA) formulated based on the cell\ntransmission model. The algorithm distributes SODTA into local sub-problems,\nwho find optimal values for their decision variables within an intersection.\nEach sub-problem communicates with its immediate neighbors to reach a consensus\non the values of common decision variables. A sub-problem receives proposed\nvalues for common decision variables from all adjacent sub-problems and\nincorporates them into its own offered values by weighted averaging and\nenforcing a gradient step to minimize its objective function. Then, the updated\nvalues are projected onto the feasible region of the sub-problems. The\nalgorithm finds high quality solutions in all tested scenarios with a finite\nnumber of iterations. The algorithm is tested on a case study network under\ndifferent demand levels and finds solutions with at most a 5% optimality gap.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 29 Dec 2021 03:54:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-30"}
