{"id":"2201.00615","submitter":"Aric BehzadCanaanie","authors":"Aric BehzadCanaanie","title":"Riemann's Last Theorem","comments":"10 pages (https://www.rslt.me/)","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The central idea of this article is to introduce and prove a special form of\nthe zeta function as proof of Riemann's last theorem. The newly proposed zeta\nfunction contains two sub functions, namely $f_1(b,s)$ and $f_2(b,s)$. The\nunique property of $\\zeta(s)=f_1(b,s)-f_2(b,s)$ is that as tends toward\ninfinity the equality $\\zeta(s)=\\zeta(1-s)$ is transformed into an exponential\nexpression for the zeros of the zeta function. At the limiting point, we simply\ndeduce that the exponential equality is satisfied if and only if\n$\\mathfrak{R}(s)=1/2$. Consequently, we conclude that the zeta function cannot\nbe zero if $\\mathfrak{R}(s)\\ne 1/2$, hence proving Riemann's last theorem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 28 Dec 2021 18:25:32 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 10 Feb 2022 20:27:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-14"}
